1 _OID 0e6cbe98-6cbe-4492-ad3a-5bd511c93f44
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="4"&gt;&amp;quot;Richard Creech IV was born in New Hanover Co. N.C. and died 1808 in Barnwell Co. S.C. He served as Senator from the Winton District, S.C. 1806-1808 and died in this office. He serv
2 CONC ed in the Revolution as Lt then Cpt. 1779-1782; also supplied provisions. Appointed Sheriff of Winton Nov. 2 1790. South Carolina House of Representatives Winton 1795-1798. Justice of Peace Coroner of Barnwell Co. 1801-1802. Commissioner of publi
2 CONC c buildings and commissioner of roads. He died Jan. 6, 1808. He received land grants recorded at Columbia State as follows: Oct. 5, 1789- 236 acres; Aug. 11,1788 264 acres; Dec. 4,1797- 148 acres; Dec. 6, 1796- 376 acres; Sept. 1797-140 acres. Thes
2 CONC e grants were in Barnwell &amp;amp; Allendale counties S.C. He married Mary Williams, a cousin, of Barnwell County. He is buried in the Revolutionary war Cemetery at the Barnwell Courthouse along with his brother William Creech. Both graves are mar
2 CONC ked by the D.A.R. There are 35 graves in the cemetery. Originally Barnwell Co. was part of Granville Co. Later part of Orangeburg District Winton Co. was created March 12, 1785. Justices William Robison, Thomas Knight, Richard Treadways, Daniel Gre
2 CONC en, William Ruford and James Blair were directed to erect a courthouse, gaol, pillow, whipping post and stocks. These were built of pine logs; Winton County became Barnwell District in 1798 and Barnwell Co. in 1868.&amp;quot;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
2 CONC &lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="4"&gt;[Excerpt from &amp;quot;The Creech Family History&amp;quot;, by James S. Creech.]&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="4"&gt;Richard Creech (III) served in the Revolutionary War in South Carolina&amp;#39;s Upp
2 CONC er Granville Regiment. Records refer to him as Richard Creech, Sr. His son, Richard Creech (IV), also served in that military Unit; records refer to him as Richard Creech, Jr. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;font size="4"&gt;Records indicate th
2 CONC e Upper Granville Regiment was involved in military actions including sieges of Savannah and Augusta, GA and actions in NC and TN.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
