2 TITL James Lawrence Williams
1 _OID 2dbc45aa-eabf-4664-852c-99638107972f
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-indent: 0.5in; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif" size="3" color="#000000"&gt;James Lawrenc
2 CONC e was the youngest surviving son of &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Wilson&lt;/span&gt; Williams and the only sur&amp;shy;viving son of his 3rd wife, Esther (Roberts) Williams.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;When Wilson died in 1836, his per
2 CONC sonal estate was sold for division among his legatees.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;It is not clear about the &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&lt;font color="#333333"&gt;home place&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt; in the records. The records do n
2 CONC ot show how much acreage James Lawrence inherited from his father (estate settled in 1854), but in cash he received $334.19 &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;estate papers &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Wilson&lt;/span&gt; Willia
2 CONC ms&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&amp;mdash;&lt;/span&gt;Administration Index,Bundle 64, &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Pkg.&lt;/span&gt; 5). R.C. Roberts, Esther&amp;rsquo;s brother bought up the furniture and kitchen equipment.&lt;span&gt
2 CONC ;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;He could have been buying it for Esther.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;At any rate, Esther stayed on in the homeplace, which was in the lower Savannah River section of the county, after &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&
2 CONC gt;Wilson&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&amp;#39;s&lt;/span&gt; death.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;By 1848 the other children of Esther had either left home or died.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;span style="font-fa
2 CONC mily: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif" size="3" color="#000000"&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde g
2 CONC othic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;In 184
2 CONC 8, she built a &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&lt;font color="#333333"&gt;2-room&lt;/font&gt; &lt;/span&gt;log house &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;lat&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;e&lt;/span&gt;r known as the &amp;quot;W
2 CONC illiams Place&amp;quot;) in Allendale.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;She owned most of the land where Allendale now stands.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Her only living son, James Lawrence, is with her and is married, with one child, Wil
2 CONC son in the 1850 census&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Esther is listed as head of the household.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;(1850 Census of Barnwell District household 355.) In 1866 JL Wi
2 CONC lliams is shown to have inventoried the estate of Charles Boyles. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif
2 CONC "&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-indent: 0.5in; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3
2 CONC "&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;In 1870 Esther deeded to her son, James Lawrence, 700 acres (XX 626--have copy) which must have been her inheritance from Wilson.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Thi
2 CONC s included the Allendale log house and its out buildings.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;A room and porch had been added then a &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;breezeway&lt;/span&gt; connecting the 2-room clapboard addition.&lt;span&gt;&amp;
2 CONC nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;There is a foundation for another room that was never built.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;There was a gristmill, which brought in farmers to get their corn ground.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Two corncribs, a gin hou
2 CONC se, a dairy house and a smoke house were also on the premises, as well as stock pens, 2 lots and barns.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;This old place is written up extensively (5 pages) in &lt;u&gt;Allendale on the Savannah.&lt;/u&gt; When &lt;
2 CONC span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Sherman&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&amp;#39;s&lt;/span&gt; army came through Allendale, they set fire to this house, but it didn&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;t burn.&lt;s
2 CONC pan&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;The original structure is completely mortised and pegged--with&amp;shy;out a single nail.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;There was a well on the property used by all the neighbors.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&
2 CONC gt;It is still there.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;/font&gt
2 CONC ;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-indent: 0.5in; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-seri
2 CONC f"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;James Lawrence was one of the 1st citizens of the New &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Allendale.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;He was on a committee of three to legally organize and establish t
2 CONC he town of Allen&amp;shy;dale, &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;SC.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Old Allendale was called &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Buddenville.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;His mothe
2 CONC r, Esther Williams, was the 1st postmistress of Allendale, dispens&amp;shy;ing mail from her own front porch.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;There is an Esther Street in Allendale named for her.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&
2 CONC lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/spa
2 CONC n&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-indent: 0.5in; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;J
2 CONC ames Lawrence Williams does not come through as strong a character as his father.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;A doting mother spoiled him.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;But he contributed a great deal to the development of the New Allen
2 CONC dale, and he was part of its first govern&amp;shy;ment.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;He gave 50 acres in 1872, for the town and laid out the street plans in the deed.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&
2 CONC lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-indent: 0.5in; text-align: justify"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-align: justify"&gt
2 CONC ;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;James Lawrence Williams is in the records many times.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;He bu
2 CONC ys and sells land in 1875.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;He set up each son &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;3) in business in &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Allendale. &lt;/span&gt;His mother, Esther, must have been an ast
2 CONC ute business woman.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;She sells to John &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;McPhail&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;(Bk.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;D-146)&lt;/span&gt; in 1850.&lt
2 CONC ;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Again in 1859 &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;(Bk&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;MM-441)&lt;/span&gt; 12A for $1,524.00 &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;have copy).&lt;span&gt;&am
2 CONC p;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;The land that she and her son got from &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Wilson&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&amp;#39;s&lt;/span&gt; estate was in the Savannah River and &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Coo
2 CONC sahatchie&lt;/span&gt; River areas of &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Barnwell&lt;/span&gt; County.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Here was where Wilson&amp;#39;s father, &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Britton&lt;/span&gt; Williams&amp;#
2 CONC 39; &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;spelled &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Brittian&lt;/span&gt; also) original acreage &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;was, which&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Wilson&lt;/sp
2 CONC an&gt; inherited.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Also, Wilson&amp;#39;s first land grant was here. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;
2 CONC font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-s
2 CONC erif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;It&amp;#39;s easy to see that Esther&amp;#39;s favorite child was James Lawrence.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;She gave James Lawrence 20 shares of stock in the Port Royal Railroad, &lt;span style="color
2 CONC : #007f00"&gt;&amp;mdash;&lt;/span&gt;later worthless. James Lawrence deeded this &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;home place&lt;/span&gt; to son, Paul Al&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;l&lt;/span&gt;en Williams.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/spa
2 CONC n&gt;Paul&amp;#39;s spinster daughter, Lena Williams, lived there until her death in 1963.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;The house stands empty, all out buildings are gone.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Vandals have left the place in sa
2 CONC d repair.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;It sits on an overgrown lot in the center of what is now Allendale&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&amp;#39;s&lt;/span&gt; nicest residential area, like a haunting specter of another time. It is one o
2 CONC f &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Barnwell&lt;/span&gt; County&amp;#39;s historical landmarks that should be restored and preserved.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;Unfortunately, all my efforts in this direction have failed, which is most fr
2 CONC ustrating.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;It can&amp;#39;t last the ravages of time in its present deteriorating condition, even though the hand-hewn logs and pegged construc&amp;shy;tion is still very solid at this writing.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbs
2 CONC p; &lt;/span&gt;But vagrants make use of the old building, and it will surely be lost by fire, if not age.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;This property is currently owned by Mrs. Richard &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Moorer&lt;/span&gt; o
2 CONC f &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Reevesville,&lt;/span&gt; SC. and her brother, &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;Dr, &lt;/span&gt;Herbert &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;&lt;font color="#333333"&gt;Smoak&lt;/font&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; of &lt;s
2 CONC pan style="color: #007f00"&gt;Orangeburg,&lt;/span&gt; SC&lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;.,&lt;/span&gt; great grandchildren of James Lawrence Williams.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; text-i
2 CONC ndent: 0.5in; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'itc avant garde gothic'"&gt;&lt;font size="3"&gt;&lt;font face="arial,helvetica,sans-serif"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;In 27 Oct 1878 JL Williams was a member of Swallow Savann
2 CONC ah Methodist Church and on 24 April 1881 he paid $12.15 for a cemetery fence for the Swallow Savannah Methodist Church cemetery.&lt;span&gt;&amp;nbsp; &lt;/span&gt;On 10 Nov 1887 he was on the building Committee of Swallow Savannah Methodist Church
2 CONC . &lt;span style="color: #007f00"&gt;He&lt;/span&gt; gave the land for the Swallow Savannah Methodist Church in 1890 however this wooden building was destroyed by fire in 1942. &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;spa
