2 TITL Ordinance of Secession signed by Joseph Brabham husband of Susan Elizabeth McMillan daughter of Gatsy &amp; Henry McMillan
1 _OID 97f5a6c8-8ff2-43ce-9da4-5a4d414c36b5
1 DATE 1817
1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>Mrs. Betty Jane Miller, ( Ayer) presented Mizpah a Copy of the Ordinance of Secession. The article is signed by 171 men.&amp;nbsp; Joseph Josiah Brabham, was one of the men who signed the article, born 06 Sep. 1817 die
2 CONC d 08 July 1883. He was married to Susannah Elizabeth McMillan, daughter of&amp;nbsp; Henry and Gatsey Anne&amp;nbsp;Moye McMillan. Mrs. Brabham was born 27 May 1827 and died 18 September 1889 in Barnwell County, S.C.&amp;nbsp;Both are&amp;nbsp;buri
2 CONC ed at Mizpah. Mr. J. J. Brabham was a well respected man in the Barnwell District and across the state as well. He was one of the&amp;nbsp;five men chosen to represent&amp;nbsp; Barnwell District at the Secession Convention of 1860. After due delib
2 CONC eration he signed along with 168 others&amp;nbsp;the ordinance severing ties between the Palmetto State and the United States of America on 20 Dec. 1860. &lt;span style="font-size: small"&gt;He organized a company at Bufords Bridge of which he wa
2 CONC s elected as captain. After service in Charleston at Coles Island , he resigned&amp;nbsp;and returned home. He was elected&amp;nbsp;to the House of Representatives&amp;nbsp; in 1861 and&amp;nbsp;1863 serving until the Constitution Convention of 186
2 CONC 5. In 1875 Brabham was elected&amp;nbsp; Clerk of Court&amp;nbsp;of Barnwell County and died serving his second term.&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;</line></content></metadataxml>
