1 _META <metadataxml><content><line>&lt;p&gt;From: http://wc.rootsweb.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/igm.cgi?op=GET&amp;amp;db=garyscottcollins&amp;amp;id=I650787066&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'times new roman'; font-size: medium; text-align: -we
2 CONC bkit-"&gt;Name: Johannes Nicholas PRESTER ( PRIESTER)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'times new roman'; text-align: -webkit-; font-size: medium"&gt;Title: I&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'times new roman'; t
2 CONC ext-align: -webkit-; font-size: medium"&gt;Sex: M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'times new roman'; text-align: -webkit-; font-size: medium"&gt;Birth: in Rhine Palatine District&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span style="font-family
2 CONC : 'times new roman'; text-align: -webkit-; font-size: medium"&gt;Death: 1782 in Charles Town, SC&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: 'times new roman'; text-align: -webkit-; font-size: medium"&gt;Sailed from Germany wit
2 CONC h a group of immigrants headed by John Jacob Riemensperger on board the Griffin (Griffith) in August of 1749. They landed at Charles Town on Oct 17, 1749. They were Protestants. The list of paid passengers is recorded in the South Carolina Counci
2 CONC l Journal, Vol XVIII, pages 661-663. Nicholas last name was misspelled as Presler in the written land plat. He was granted 150 acres of land in or near Saxagothe Township (Dutch Fork). This tract was between the Broad and Saluda Rivers and was ta
2 CONC x free for the first ten years. Priester&amp;#39;s Creek was named for him. Most of the info regarding Nicholas comes from the Priester Book compiled by Jane Priester Hawkins.&lt;/span&gt;</line></content></metadataxml>
